House Price Prediction in Boulder, CO

Xiaoyi Wu

10/20/2021

01. Introduction & Motivation

1.1 Brief introduction of Boulder County

As one of the most popular real estate websites in the United States, Zillow and its affiliates offer customers an on-demand experience for selling, buying, renting and financing with transparency and nearly seamless end-to-end service. These years, Zillow has produced home value reports for the U.S. and over 130 metropolitan statistical areas. The reports identify market trends including, but not limited to: 5- and 10-year annualized change, negative equity, short sales and foreclosure transactions.

However, Zillow has realized that its housing market predictions are not as accurate as they would like. Thus, here, we build a regression model to help Zillow predict the sale price of housing in Boulder County, Colorado between 2019 and 2021.

Here are several main characteristics of the Boulder County housing market:

1. Close proximity to Denver: The Boulder real estate market has all the earmarks of being sustainable. It has benefited a lot from its close proximity to Denver and the employment rate of Boulder County is well above the national average.

2. Abundant landscape features from farmland to rolling grasslands in the plains: Boulder County is close to Rocky Mountains. U.S. Route 36 from Denver with its iconic sandstone slabs rising from the mountains, prefaced by pine-clad mesas and cradled within the backdrop of the snow-capped Indian Peaks provide around 2000 miles of hiking trials and massive green space to Boulder County.

3. Livable metro areas: In the metro area, there are roughly 300,000 people. The district has seen growth as people move from the expensive, over-crowded Denver area to Boulder County where you can still hike in the mountains and see the hills. Boulder County ranks second in Best Places to live for quality of life in U.S. News.

Therefore, considering the characteristics mentioned above, we adopt a geospatial machine learning model to incorporate natural resources distribution and neighborhood effects with socio-economic factors to predict the house prices in various areas of the county.

tracts2019 <- get_acs(geography = "tract", variables = c("B25026_001E","B02001_002E",
                                             "B19013_001E","B25058_001E",
                                             "B06012_002E", 
                                             # vacant variables
                                             "B25002_003E", 
                                             "B25004_002E","B25004_003E",
                                             "B25004_004E","B25004_005E",
                                             # total housing unit
                                             "B25001_001E",
                                             # renter occupied 
                                             'B08137_003E'), 
          year=2019, state= 08, county= 013, geometry=T, output="wide") %>%
  st_transform(st_crs(boulder.sf)) %>%
  rename(TotalPop = B25026_001E, 
         Whites = B02001_002E,
         MedHHInc = B19013_001E, 
         MedRent = B25058_001E,
         TotalPoverty = B06012_002E,
         TotalVacant = B25002_003E,
         ForRent = B25004_002E,
         ForRentVac = B25004_003E,
         ForSale = B25004_004E,
         ForSaleVac = B25004_005E,
         TotalUnit = B25001_001E,
         RenterOccupied = B08137_003E
         ) %>%
  dplyr::select(-NAME, -starts_with("B")) %>%
  mutate(pctWhite = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, Whites / TotalPop,0),
         pctPoverty = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, TotalPoverty / TotalPop, 0),
         pctTotalVacant = ifelse(TotalUnit > 0, TotalVacant / TotalUnit * 100, 0),
         TotalOccupied = TotalUnit - TotalVacant,
        pctRenterOccupied = ifelse(TotalOccupied >0, RenterOccupied/TotalOccupied, 0)) %>%
  dplyr::select(-Whites, -TotalPoverty) 

projected.tracts2019 <-  
    tracts2019 %>%  
 st_transform(st_crs(boulder.sf))

2.2 Feature engineering

Feature engineering is the process of transforming raw data into features which influence the value of the dependent variable. In this project, we take the internal house conditions, socio-economic factors, and proximity to amenities and public services into models and conduct feature engineering on these raw data. Especially, we use ‘nn_function’ to calculate the average nearest neighbor distance from each house to its k(k=1,2,3,4,5) nearest neighbor crimes.

st_c <- st_coordinates

boulder.sf <-
  boulder.sf %>% 
    mutate(
      health_nn1 = nn_function(st_c(boulder.s), st_c(Health_facility.sf), 1),
      health_nn2 = nn_function(st_c(boulder.s), st_c(Health_facility.sf), 2), 
      health_nn3 = nn_function(st_c(boulder.s), st_c(Health_facility.sf), 3), 
      health_nn4 = nn_function(st_c(boulder.s), st_c(Health_facility.sf), 4), 
      health_nn5 = nn_function(st_c(boulder.s), st_c(Health_facility.sf), 5))

2.3 Correlation matrix

After all the potential related features are set, we conduct exploratory analysis to generate feature combination. We create multiple correlation matrices to visualize the correlation between independent variables and develop scatter plots to visualize the linearity between independent variables and house prices.Finally, We select variables which have lower correlation (\(-0.6<R^2<0.6\)) with other independent variables and linear relationship with dependent variable as the features in our prediction models.

2.3.1 All features

From the correlation matrix below, dark blue indicates two features are strongly and positively correlated with each other, while dark green indicates a strongly negative correlation. White means there is no correlation between the features.

numericVars.all<-
  select_if(all.feature.list,is.numeric)%>%
  na.omit()

ggcorrplot(
  round(cor(numericVars.all), 2), 
  p.mat = cor_pmat(numericVars.all),
  colors = c('#05A167', "white", '#6897BB'),
  lab_size = 1,
  tl.cex = 5,
  type="lower",
  insig = c("pch", "blank"), pch = 1, pch.col = "black", pch.cex =1) +  
  labs(title = "Correlation across numeric variables\n(All features)\n") +
  plotTheme()

2.3.5 Home price as a function of four numeric features

For the plots below, We choose “percentage of white people”,“number of bedroom”,“the quality code”,“number of main floor” as x axis of each plot respectively and the house price as the y axis. The result shows that the houses with larger main floor area and more bedrooms and higher quality code in higher-percentage of white-people neighborhood tend to be more expensive.

features <- c('percentage of White','bedroom number','quality code','main floor square')
names(features)<-c('pctWhite','nbrBedRoom','qualityCode','mainfloorSF')

price.house.plot <- 
  st_drop_geometry(train_data) %>% 
  dplyr::select(price, pctWhite, nbrBedRoom,qualityCode,mainfloorSF) %>%
  filter(price <= 5000000) %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -price) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(Value, price)) +
  geom_point(size = .5) + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se=F, colour = "darkred") +
  facet_wrap(~Variable, ncol = 2, scales = "free",
             labeller = labeller(Variable = features)) +
  plotTheme() + 
  labs(title = "House Price as a Function of 4 variables")

03. Methods

Here, we adopt geospatial machine learning models to predict house price with the existing data as accurate and generalized as possible. We firstly build a ordinary least squares regression model with several features,them try to adjust selected features to optimization model. The main measurements we considered are residual standard error, \(R^2\), mean absolute error(MAE), and p-value. MAE is calculated by taking the mean of the absolute values of subtracting each predicted housing prices from the corresponding given prices in the testing dataset. Residual standard is the error of the coefficient, which helps us understand how reliable the coefficient is. The p-value tells us whether the variable is a useful predictor, and \(R^2\) is a percentage ‘goodness of fit’ indicator. In addtion, we use k-fold cross validation to see whether the model is generalized or not, whether the residual are spatial correlated or not.

4.6 Spatial Automation

We use three methods to detect spatial automation in our model.
01. Map of residuals: map the residuals around the boulder;
02. Spatial lags plot: map the average neighboring values of house prices;
03. Moran’s I:map the correlation coefficient that measures the overall spatial autocorrelation of the data.

4.6.1 Map of residuals

Through the map we can see that the residuals tend to cluster in urban districts,northeastern and southeastern of Boulder county.

map_residual<- ggplot()+
  geom_sf(data=boulder.boundary)+
  geom_sf(data=model_test2,
          aes(color=q5(SalePrice.Error)),
          show.legend = "point",size = 1)+  
                    scale_color_manual(values =  c(palette),
                     labels = qBr(model_test2,'SalePrice.Error'),
                     name = "Residuals") +
  labs(title = 'Map of residuals on test set\n') +
  mapTheme() + 
  plotTheme()
map_residual

4.6.2 Spatial lags

Spatial lag is a variable that averages the neighboring values of a location. In this case, we use census tract units as the neighborhood. The following figure plots SalePrice as a function of spatial lag. The interpretation of this plot is that as price increases, so does the price of nearby houses.

## Spatial lag in errors: average errors in five nearest neighbors
k_nearest_neighbors = 5
# average errors in five nearest neighbors
coords.test <- st_centroid(st_geometry(model_test2),
                           of_largest_polygon=TRUE)

neighborList.test <- knn2nb(knearneigh(coords.test, k_nearest_neighbors))

spatialWeights.test <- nb2listw(neighborList.test, style="W") 


model_test2$lagPriceError <- lag.listw(spatialWeights.test,model_test2$SalePrice.Error)

error.spatial.lag <- ggplot(model_test2, 
                            aes(x = lagPriceError, y = SalePrice.Error)) +
  geom_point(colour = "black") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, colour = "darkred") +
  labs(title = "Error on Test Set as a function of the Spatial Lag of Price\n",
       x = "Spatial lag of errors (Mean error of 5 nearest neighbors)",
       y = "Errors of Sale Price") +
  plotTheme()

error.spatial.lag

4.6.3 Moran’s I

In our model, the Moran’s I is 0.2383. To assess the significance of the Moran’s I statistic against a null hypothesis of no spatial autocorrelation, we randomly permuted Moran’s I for 999 times and plotted them as a histogram with the Observations. The pseudo p-value is 0.001, which indicates that we can reject the null hypothesis that the the house price is randomly distributed, that is there really is spatial autocorrelation in house price.

moranTest <- moran.mc(model_test2$SalePrice.AbsError, 
                      spatialWeights.test, nsim = 999)

moran.plot <- ggplot(as.data.frame(moranTest$res[c(1:999)]), 
                     aes(moranTest$res[c(1:999)])) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.01) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = moranTest$statistic), colour = "orange",size=1) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(-1, 1)) +
  labs(title="Observed and permuted Moran's I",
       subtitle= "Observed Moran's I in orange, I = 0.2383",
       x="Moran's I",
       y="Count") +
  plotTheme()
moran.plot

4.10.3 Generalizability in different contexts

Combined with the demographic data,we discuss algorithm fairness in race and income contexts. We found the neighborhood model can show better performance while it has lower accuracy in high-income group.

census <-   train_data %>% 
  mutate(raceContext = ifelse(pctWhite > .5, "Majority White", "Majority Non-White"),
          incomeContext = ifelse(MedHHInc > mean(MedHHInc,na.rm = T), "High Income", "Low Income")) %>%
  select(raceContext,incomeContext)

race.group <- st_join(bothRegressions, census) %>%
  group_by(Regression, raceContext) %>%
  dplyr::summarize(mean.MAPE = scales::percent(mean(SalePrice.APE, na.rm = T))) %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  spread(raceContext, mean.MAPE) %>%
  kable(caption = "\nTest set MAPE by Neighborhood Racial Context") %>%

05. Discussion and conclusion

We would like to recommend our neighborhood model to Zillow as it incorporates spatial features and performed well on either accuracy or generalization with fairly low MAPE in different contexts

However, we have to admit that there are still several aspects we need to improve in the future.

First, we should include more features of natural resource distribution such as .. in our algorithm.

Second, we could further transform the non-Gaussian distribution data.

Third, the linear regression model we use here simplifies the complex patterns in the real-world case. Thus, we should implement non-linear regression models to capture data representation and forecast the house prices more accurately.
